Doppler Signature of a Rotating Wind Turbine¶

Introduction¶

This notebook demonstrates the simulation and analysis of Doppler signatures from rotating wind turbines—a critical challenge for radar systems operating near wind farms. Understanding turbine Doppler characteristics is essential for air traffic control, weather radar, and military surveillance systems.

The Doppler Effect in Rotating Targets¶

The Doppler effect describes the frequency shift that occurs when there is relative motion between a radar and a target. For rotating objects like wind turbines, this creates complex, time-varying Doppler signatures.

Doppler Frequency Formula:

$$f_d = \frac{2v_r}{\lambda} = \frac{2v_r f_c}{c}$$

Where:

  • $f_d$ = Doppler frequency shift (Hz)
  • $v_r$ = Radial velocity (m/s)
  • $\lambda$ = Radar wavelength (m)
  • $f_c$ = Carrier frequency (Hz)
  • $c$ = Speed of light (3×10⁸ m/s)

Wind Turbine Doppler Characteristics¶

Wind turbines present unique challenges for radar systems:

1. Micro-Doppler Signatures

  • Blade tip velocity: Can reach 80-100 m/s for large turbines
  • Maximum Doppler: ±300 Hz or more at 24 GHz
  • Periodic modulation: Blade rotation creates time-varying returns
  • Flash effect: Peak returns when blades are perpendicular to radar

2. Doppler Spread

  • Wide bandwidth: Turbines create Doppler spread of several hundred Hz
  • Continuous spectrum: Multiple scatterers moving at different velocities
  • Time-varying: Pattern repeats with blade rotation period
  • Symmetry: Three-blade turbines show characteristic triplet pattern

3. Interference Issues

  • Clutter: Strong stationary returns from tower and nacelle
  • Aircraft masking: Turbine Doppler can overlap aircraft signatures
  • Radar blanking: Wind farms can create detection gaps
  • False alarms: Rotating blades mimic moving targets

Physical Mechanisms¶

Scattering from Turbine Components:

  1. Tower: Stationary, zero Doppler (DC component)
  2. Nacelle: Minimal motion, near-zero Doppler
  3. Hub: Rotation axis, low radial velocity
  4. Blades: High tangential velocity creates strong Doppler
  5. Blade tips: Maximum velocity, peak Doppler shifts

Blade Geometry Effects:

  • Approaching blade: Positive Doppler (moving toward radar)
  • Receding blade: Negative Doppler (moving away from radar)
  • Horizontal blade: Zero radial velocity, minimal Doppler
  • Time variation: Doppler oscillates with rotation period

Applications and Impact¶

Air Traffic Control:

  • Turbine clutter interferes with aircraft detection
  • Doppler processing can separate aircraft from turbine returns
  • Wind farm sites require careful radar planning

Weather Radar:

  • Turbine signatures contaminate precipitation measurements
  • Velocity estimates affected by turbine Doppler
  • Filtering techniques needed to remove turbine clutter

Military Surveillance:

  • Wind farms create radar coverage gaps
  • Low-flying aircraft detection degraded
  • Electronic countermeasures considerations

Mitigation Techniques:

  • Doppler filtering: Remove known turbine Doppler ranges
  • Spatial filtering: Beamforming to null turbine directions
  • Signal processing: Advanced clutter suppression algorithms
  • Radar siting: Avoid wind farm corridors

You'll Learn How To:¶

  • Configure a continuous wave (CW) radar for Doppler detection
  • Model rotating wind turbine targets with time-varying geometry
  • Simulate radar returns from rotating blades using ray tracing
  • Extract time-domain I/Q baseband signals
  • Apply Short-Time Fourier Transform (STFT) for time-frequency analysis
  • Generate spectrograms to visualize Doppler evolution
  • Interpret micro-Doppler signatures from rotating targets
  • Understand blade flash effects and periodic modulation

About This Example¶

This notebook uses RadarSimPy to simulate a 24 GHz CW radar observing a rotating wind turbine. We'll:

  1. Configure a simple CW radar system
  2. Model a 3-blade turbine rotating at 50°/s
  3. Simulate radar returns using sample-level ray tracing
  4. Analyze I/Q baseband signals
  5. Generate spectrograms showing Doppler evolution
  6. Observe characteristic blade flash patterns

The simulation demonstrates how rotating blades create distinctive time-varying Doppler signatures that can interfere with radar operations.

Radar System Configuration¶

Configure a continuous wave (CW) radar for Doppler detection of the rotating turbine.

Import Required Modules¶

Import necessary RadarSimPy modules and NumPy for numerical operations.

In [ ]:
# Import necessary modules for radar simulation
import numpy as np
from radarsimpy import Radar, Transmitter, Receiver

Transmitter Configuration¶

Configure a continuous wave (CW) transmitter for Doppler radar operation.

CW Radar Characteristics:

  • No range resolution (single frequency)
  • Excellent Doppler resolution
  • Simple, low-cost implementation
  • Ideal for velocity measurement

Waveform Definition:

For a CW radar, the frequency is constant throughout the transmission. In RadarSimPy, this is specified as:

  • f: Carrier frequency (Hz)
  • t: Pulse duration (s)

The transmitter continuously radiates at the carrier frequency during the observation period.

Transmitter Parameters:

  • Frequency: 24.125 GHz (ISM band, K-band)
  • Duration: 20 seconds (long observation for Doppler analysis)
  • Transmit Power: 20 dBm (~100 mW)
  • Pulses: 1 (continuous transmission)
  • Antenna: Single channel at origin
In [ ]:
# Configure CW transmitter
tx = Transmitter(
    f=24.125e9,  # Carrier frequency: 24.125 GHz (K-band)
    t=20,        # Transmission duration: 20 seconds
    tx_power=20, # Transmit power: 20 dBm
    pulses=1,    # Single continuous pulse
    channels=[dict(location=(0, 0, 0))]  # Single antenna at origin
)

Receiver Configuration¶

Configure the receiver for baseband I/Q sampling and Doppler processing.

Receiver Parameters:

  • Sampling Rate (fs): 800 Hz

    • Nyquist rate determines maximum detectable Doppler
    • Max Doppler = fs/2 = 400 Hz
    • Sufficient for turbine blade velocities at 24 GHz

  • Noise Figure: 4 dB

    • Receiver noise performance
    • Lower values improve SNR

  • RF Gain: 20 dB

    • Amplification in RF stage
    • Boosts weak turbine returns

  • Baseband Gain: 50 dB

    • Post-mixing amplification
    • Prepares signal for ADC

  • Load Resistor: 1000 Ω

    • Converts RF power to voltage
    • Affects signal amplitude

Sampling Considerations:

  • 800 Hz sampling over 20 seconds = 16,000 samples
  • Doppler resolution: ~1/20s = 0.05 Hz
  • Unambiguous Doppler range: ±400 Hz
In [ ]:
# Configure receiver for Doppler detection
rx = Receiver(
    fs=800,                          # Sampling rate: 800 Hz
    noise_figure=4,                  # Noise figure: 4 dB
    rf_gain=20,                      # RF gain: 20 dB
    baseband_gain=50,                # Baseband gain: 50 dB
    load_resistor=1000,              # Load resistance: 1000 Ω
    channels=[dict(location=(0, 0, 0))]  # Single receive antenna at origin
)

Create Radar System¶

Combine the transmitter and receiver to form the complete CW Doppler radar.

In [ ]:
# Create radar system by combining transmitter and receiver
radar = Radar(transmitter=tx, receiver=rx)

Wind Turbine Target Model¶

Configure a rotating wind turbine target with time-varying blade positions.

Target Configuration Parameters¶

Geometric Properties:

  • Model: 3D mesh of 3-blade wind turbine
  • Location: 8 meters from radar (x-axis)
  • Orientation: Initial rotation angle specified

Motion Parameters:

  1. Rotation Angle (time-varying):

    • Yaw: 0° (no rotation around vertical axis)
    • Pitch: 50 × timestamp (°) — rotating blades
    • Roll: 0° (no tilt)
    • Rotation varies with time to simulate continuous blade motion

  2. Rotation Rate: (0, 0, 0) °/s

    • Not used since rotation is specified per sample via timestamp
    • Alternative to time-varying rotation angle

  3. Linear Speed: (0, 0, 0) m/s

    • Turbine is stationary (not translating)
    • Only rotational motion is modeled

Rotation Mechanics:

The blade rotation angle is computed as:

rotation_angle = 50 × radar.time_prop["timestamp"]

This creates time-varying blade positions where:

  • At t = 0s: angle = 0°
  • At t = 1s: angle = 50°
  • At t = 20s: angle = 1000° (2.78 full rotations)

Blade Tip Velocity Calculation:

For a typical turbine with blade radius R ≈ 1m and ω = 50°/s:

  • Angular velocity: ω = 50°/s × (π/180) = 0.873 rad/s
  • Tip velocity: v = ωR ≈ 0.873 m/s
  • Maximum Doppler: f_d = 2v/λ ≈ 140 Hz at 24 GHz
In [ ]:
# Configure rotating wind turbine target
target_1 = {
    "model": "../models/turbine.stl",  # 3D model of 3-blade turbine
    "unit": "m",                        # Model units in meters
    "location": (8, 0, 0),             # Position 8m along x-axis
    "rotation": [0, 50 * radar.time_prop["timestamp"], 0],  # Time-varying blade rotation
    "rotation_rate": (0, 0, 0),        # Static (rotation handled by timestamp)
    "speed": (0, 0, 0),                # No translational motion
}

# Create target list for simulation
targets = [target_1]

Radar Scene Simulation¶

Simulate the radar returns from the rotating turbine using sample-level ray tracing.

Simulation Parameters¶

Ray Tracing Configuration:

  • Level: 'sample' — Most accurate but computationally intensive

    • Computes ray paths for each ADC sample point
    • Captures instantaneous blade positions
    • Essential for time-varying Doppler analysis

  • Density: 2 rays per wavelength²

    • Controls ray tracing accuracy vs. computation time
    • Higher density = better accuracy, longer computation

Alternative Levels:

  • 'pulse': Ray tracing per pulse (faster, less accurate for rotating targets)
  • 'frame': Single ray trace per frame (fastest, not suitable for rotation)

Output Data Structure:

The simulation returns a dictionary with:

  • timestamp: Time stamps for each sample [channels, pulses, samples]
  • baseband: Complex I/Q samples [channels, pulses, samples]
  • noise: System noise contribution [channels, pulses, samples]

For our configuration:

  • Channels: 1 (single Tx/Rx pair)
  • Pulses: 1 (continuous transmission)
  • Samples: 16,000 (800 Hz × 20 s)

Expected Computation Time:

Sample-level ray tracing is computationally intensive:

  • Typical runtime: 30-120 seconds depending on hardware
  • Progress displayed during execution
  • Trade-off between accuracy and speed
In [ ]:
# Import radar simulator and timing module
from radarsimpy.simulator import sim_radar
import time

# Start timing
tic = time.time()

# Simulate radar returns from rotating turbine
# level='sample': Ray tracing for each time sample (most accurate)
# density=2: 2 rays per wavelength² for accuracy
data = sim_radar(radar, targets, density=2, level="sample")

# Extract baseband I/Q signals and add system noise
baseband = data["baseband"] + data["noise"]  # Complex samples (I + jQ)
timestamp = data["timestamp"]                # Time stamps for each sample

# End timing
toc = time.time()

# Display execution time
print("Exec time: " + str(toc - tic) + " s")

Exec time :97.75135922431946s

Visualize Baseband I/Q Signals¶

Plot the in-phase (I) and quadrature (Q) components of the received signal to observe time-domain characteristics.

I/Q Signal Interpretation:

  • I (In-phase): Real component = cos(phase)
  • Q (Quadrature): Imaginary component = sin(phase)
  • Amplitude: √(I² + Q²) indicates signal strength
  • Phase: arctan(Q/I) contains Doppler information

Expected Pattern:

For a rotating turbine, the I/Q signals will show:

  • Periodic modulation: Repeats with blade rotation period
  • Amplitude variation: Blade flash when perpendicular to radar
  • Phase changes: Encodes Doppler shifts from blade motion
  • Complexity: Multiple scatterers create interference patterns
In [ ]:
# Create figure for I/Q baseband signals
fig = go.Figure()

# Plot In-phase (I) component
fig.add_trace(
    go.Scatter(
        x=timestamp[0, 0, :],      # Time axis
        y=np.real(baseband[0, 0, :]),  # Real part (I)
        name="I (In-phase)",
        line=dict(width=1)
    )
)

# Plot Quadrature (Q) component
fig.add_trace(
    go.Scatter(
        x=timestamp[0, 0, :],          # Time axis
        y=np.imag(baseband[0, 0, :]),  # Imaginary part (Q)
        name="Q (Quadrature)",
        line=dict(width=1)
    )
)

# Configure plot layout
fig.update_layout(
    title="I/Q Baseband Signals from Rotating Turbine",
    yaxis=dict(title="Amplitude (V)"),
    xaxis=dict(title="Time (s)"),
    height=600,
    legend=dict(x=0.02, y=0.98),
)

Time-Frequency Analysis: Short-Time Fourier Transform (STFT)¶

Apply STFT to convert the time-domain signal into a time-frequency representation (spectrogram).

STFT Parameters¶

Why STFT for Rotating Targets?

Standard FFT provides frequency content but loses time information. For rotating turbines, the Doppler signature changes continuously with blade position. STFT provides time-varying frequency analysis essential for capturing blade rotation dynamics.

Parameter Selection:

  1. Window Length (nperseg): 128 samples

    • Frequency resolution: Δf = fs/nperseg = 800/128 = 6.25 Hz
    • Time window: T = nperseg/fs = 128/800 = 0.16 s
    • Trade-off: Longer → better frequency resolution, worse time resolution

  2. Overlap (noverlap): 120 samples

    • Overlap percentage: 120/128 = 93.75%
    • High overlap improves time resolution in spectrogram
    • Adjacent windows share most samples for smooth visualization

  3. FFT Length (nfft): 512 points

    • Zero-padding improves spectral interpolation
    • Final frequency bins: 512
    • Does not improve resolution, only smoothness

  4. Two-sided FFT (return_onesided=False)

    • Returns both positive and negative frequencies
    • Essential for viewing both approaching and receding blade Doppler
    • Output range: -fs/2 to +fs/2 (-400 to +400 Hz)

STFT Output:

  • Frequencies: Array of Doppler frequencies
  • Time segments: Array of time windows
  • Spectrogram: 2D complex matrix [frequency, time]
In [ ]:
# Import STFT function from scipy
from scipy.signal import stft

# Compute Short-Time Fourier Transform
spec = stft(
    baseband[0, 0, :],                           # Input I/Q signal
    fs=radar.radar_prop["receiver"].bb_prop["fs"],  # Sampling rate: 800 Hz
    nperseg=128,        # Window length: 128 samples (0.16 s)
    noverlap=120,       # Overlap: 120 samples (93.75%)
    nfft=512,           # FFT length: 512 points (zero-padded)
    return_onesided=False,  # Two-sided spectrum for ± Doppler
)

# spec[0]: Frequency array
# spec[1]: Time array
# spec[2]: Complex spectrogram matrix [frequency, time]

Visualize Doppler Spectrogram¶

Generate a spectrogram showing how Doppler frequency evolves over time as the turbine rotates.

Spectrogram Processing:

The STFT output has negative frequencies first, then positive. For intuitive visualization, we reorder to show:

  • Negative Doppler (top): Blades moving away from radar
  • Zero Doppler (middle): Stationary components
  • Positive Doppler (bottom): Blades approaching radar

Expected Spectrogram Features:

  1. DC Component (0 Hz):

    • Bright horizontal line at zero Doppler
    • Represents stationary tower and nacelle
    • Present throughout time

  2. Blade Flash Patterns:

    • Periodic bright spots at ± Doppler frequencies
    • Occur when blades are perpendicular to radar beam
    • Repeat every blade rotation period (T = 360°/50°/s = 7.2 s)

  3. Doppler Spread:

    • Range from ~-150 Hz to +150 Hz
    • Wider spread indicates faster blade rotation
    • Symmetric about zero for 3-blade symmetry

  4. Triplet Pattern:

    • Three flashes per rotation (one per blade)
    • Characteristic signature of 3-blade turbines
    • Helps identify turbine interference

  5. Time Evolution:

    • Sinusoidal modulation of Doppler frequency
    • Blade velocity component varies as sin(θ)
    • Continuous pattern over observation period
In [ ]:
# Reorder frequency axis for intuitive visualization
# Separate negative and positive frequency indices
idx_neg = np.where(spec[0] < 0)   # Negative Doppler indices
idx_pos = np.where(spec[0] >= 0)  # Positive Doppler indices

# Concatenate: negative frequencies first, then positive
dopp_ordered = spec[0][np.concatenate([idx_neg[0], idx_pos[0]])]

# Reorder spectrogram matrix to match frequency ordering
spec_shifted = spec[2][np.concatenate([idx_neg[0], idx_pos[0]]), :]

# Create spectrogram heatmap
fig = go.Figure()

fig.add_trace(
    go.Heatmap(
        z=20 * np.log10(np.abs(spec_shifted)),  # Convert to dB scale
        x=spec[1],              # Time axis (seconds)
        y=dopp_ordered,         # Doppler frequency axis (Hz)
        hoverongaps=False,      # Disable hover over missing data
        colorscale="Jet",       # Color map (blue=low, red=high)
        colorbar=dict(title="Power (dB)"),
    )
)

# Add horizontal line at zero Doppler for reference
fig.add_hline(
    y=0,
    line_dash="dash",
    line_color="white",
    line_width=1,
    annotation_text="Zero Doppler",
    annotation_position="right"
)

# Configure plot layout
fig.update_layout(
    title="Doppler Spectrogram of Rotating Wind Turbine (24 GHz)",
    yaxis=dict(title="Doppler Frequency (Hz)"),
    xaxis=dict(title="Time (s)"),
    height=700,
    margin=dict(l=10, r=10, b=10, t=40),
)

# uncomment this to display interactive plot
# fig.show()

# display static image to reduce size on radarsimx.com
img_bytes = fig.to_image(format="jpg", scale=2)
display(Image(img_bytes))
